You're correct, my apologies for the confusion - there's no need to make any changes to the index.html file as the changes we made are primarily at the JavaScript level.

As for the switchUser function, you're also correct in saying that it can be handled at a more user-focused level. The Game class does not necessarily need to be aware of the user switch action as it's primarily related to the User's state. The Game class's primary concern should be to facilitate game-related actions, and the state of the User (including switching users) could be managed by the User class itself.

You can indeed set up the event listener for user switching in the User class, and this can be done when the page is loaded or when a new User instance is created. Here's how you can do that:

```javascript
export default class User {
    // ...

    initialize() {
        this.displayBackfilledResults();
        document.querySelector("#user").textContent = 'Current user: ' + this.name;

        // Setup event listener for switching users
        document.querySelector("#switchUserButton").addEventListener('click', () => {
            const newUser = document.querySelector('#userSwitch').value;
            this.switchUser(newUser);
            document.querySelector("#user").textContent = 'Current user: ' + newUser;
        });
    }
}
```
And in your Game.js, the initialize method:

```javascript
initialize() {
    this.user.initialize();

    // Add event listeners
    document.querySelector("#startPlayingButton").addEventListener('click', () => this.startPlaying());
    document.querySelector("#backfillResultsButton").addEventListener('click', () => this.backfillResults());
}
```

In this way, the User class takes care of its own state transitions (including user switching), and the Game class doesn't need to be concerned with that.

